Notebook[{

Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Chapter 9  -  Section 9.2", "Title",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "I",
  StyleBox["n this ",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontWeight->"Bold",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  StyleBox[" notebook, you will analyze the solution to a nonlinear \
autonomous differential equation that represents an undamped pendulum. You \
will find solutions to the system by integration. These solutions will be \
plotted in the phase plane together with the direction field for the system. \
\n",
    FontWeight->"Bold"],
  "\n",
  StyleBox["In most cases, to adapt this code to other problems, you will \
have to change only the input shown in red. To open a cell grouping, \
double-click on the right-hand side of the double cell marker.",
    FontSize->14]
}], "Subsubtitle",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Problem 21:  \tdx/dt = y
\t\tdy/dt = - Sin[x]\
\>", "Section",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Finding an Implicit Solution", "Subsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
Since this system of differential equations is autonomous, we can solve for \
dy/dx as a function of x and y and get dy/dx = -Sin[x] / y. In this case, the \
variables are separable, so we can find an implicit solution using \
integration.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[{\(Clear[x, y, t, h, rhs1, rhs2]\), "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"rhs1", "=", 
        StyleBox["y",
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"rhs2", "=", 
        StyleBox[\(-Sin[x]\),
          FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], 
      ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", \(h[x_, 
        y_] = \[Integral]rhs1 \[DifferentialD]y - \[Integral]rhs2 \
\[DifferentialD]x\)}], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
Setting this h[x,y] equal to different constants will give us solution curves \
in the phase plane corresponding to different sets of initial conditions. We \
should note from the original system that the equilibrium points occur \
whenever y = 0 and x is an integral multiple of \[Pi].\
\>", "Text"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
Plotting Solution Trajectories in the Phase Plane Together with the Direction \
Field \
\>", "Subsection",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
To plot the direction field, we need to load a graphics package.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< Graphics`PlotField`\)], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
The plot of the direction field uses the right hand side of the first \
differential equation as the first input and the right hand side of the \
second differential equation as the second input. The ScaleFunction is a \
built-in option that displays the direction field well here.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"plotvf", "=", 
        RowBox[{"PlotVectorField", "[", 
          RowBox[{\({rhs1, rhs2}\), ",", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{"x", ",", 
                StyleBox[\(-15\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[",",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox["15",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], ",", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{"y", ",", 
                StyleBox[\(-5\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[",",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox["5",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], 
            ",", \(ScaleFunction \[Rule] \(( .4 &)\)\), 
            ",", \(AspectRatio \[Rule] 1\)}], "]"}]}], ";"}]], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[TextData[{
  "We will call upon the general solution in the form h(x, y) == a constant \
found above and plot several trajectories in the phase plane corresponding to \
three different sets of initial conditions. We will need to plot these \
functions implicitly, so to do this, we first load a package that is required \
for doing implicit plots. Remember that we write our equations with a double \
equal sign in the implicit plot command. You can expect to get warning \
messages about fact that inverse functions are being used as ",
  StyleBox["Mathematica",
    FontSlant->"Italic"],
  " is creating the implicit plots"
}], "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    \(<< Graphics`ImplicitPlot`\)], "Input"],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"plotsoln", "=", 
        RowBox[{"ImplicitPlot", "[", 
          RowBox[{
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{
                RowBox[{\(h[x, y]\), "\[Equal]", 
                  StyleBox["0",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ",", 
                RowBox[{\(h[x, y]\), "\[Equal]", 
                  StyleBox["1",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ",", 
                RowBox[{\(h[x, y]\), "\[Equal]", 
                  StyleBox["2",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], ",", " ", 
                RowBox[{\(h[x, y]\), "\[Equal]", 
                  StyleBox["4",
                    FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}]}], "}"}], ",", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              RowBox[{"x", ",", 
                StyleBox[\(-15\),
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox[",",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], 
                StyleBox["15",
                  FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]]}], "}"}], 
            ",", \(PlotStyle \[Rule] {Hue[ .2], Hue[ .4], Hue[ .6], 
                Hue[8]}\)}], "]"}]}], ";"}]], "Input"],

Cell["\<\
Look at how different the solution appears when we set h(x,y) is 0 or 1. Look \
back at the functions involved and see if you can determine why that happens. \
Try out the plot for different constants. 
We can plot these solutions together with the direction field. In this way, \
we can see the direction of motion of these solution curves.\
\>", "Text",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell[BoxData[
    RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"Show", "[", 
        RowBox[{"plotvf", ",", "plotsoln", ",", 
          RowBox[{"PlotRange", "\[Rule]", 
            RowBox[{"{", 
              StyleBox[\({\(-15\), 15}, {\(-5\), 5}\),
                FontColor->RGBColor[1, 0, 0]], "}"}]}], 
          ",", \(Axes \[Rule] True\), ",", \(AxesLabel \[Rule] {x, y}\)}], 
        "]"}], ";"}]], "Input",
  PageWidth->WindowWidth],

Cell["\<\
It appears that the critical points, (0, n\[Pi]), stand out in the above \
graph. Note too how setting h(x, y) equal to a constant allows for more than \
one set of initial conditions. Recall that this system of differential \
equations represents the undamped pendulum. You should keep this in mind when \
interpreting the graph.\
\>", "Text"]
}, Closed]]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]]
},
